AFL Player Roles Report

Tom Neill
2023-04-03

Like most sports, a quick Google search of ‘AFL positions’ will land you on a pretty standard image of a teams starting lineup; forwards, midfielders and defenders. But turn on a game of AFL and good luck picking out which player is in exactly which position . Players are not exactly confined to their starting position and within each team players that start in similar positions may play completely different roles for their teams. Describing a player’s role from where they start each bounce down feels a bit like asking where someone’s office is rather than what job they do.

So, is it possible to use data to define player ‘roles’ rather than positions? And is this really a better way of describing what players do compared to traditional positions?

Data

AFL is one of the most data rich sports in the world with hundreds of stats recorded every game. Unfortunately most of this data is not open source, however Matthew Moyle maintains an AFL statistical database and provides a comprehensive API through the fitzRoy package in R.

“The fitzRoy package aims to provide a consistent and reliable API to various data sources of both the Men and Women competitions of the AFL. These functions provide easy and tidy access to data such as fixtures, results and statistics from various data sources.”

Analysis

Setup

# loading relevant packages
library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(umap)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggrepel)
library(cluster)
library(factoextra)
library(plotly)

Loading data

The data used in this project is from the 2022 AFL premiership season. Player stats from this season are loaded using the fitzRoy package.

# create data frame of 2022 stats
raw_data_2022 <- fitzRoy::fetch_player_stats_fryzigg(2022)

Cleaning

This data set is known as being reliable, however, it’s still important to check. Let’s have a look at the data and make sure everything is in order.

# summary of the data
names(raw_data_2022)
# check for duplicates and make sure column names are clean
anyDuplicated(raw_data_2022)
janitor::clean_names(raw_data_2022)

Manipulating data

Looks good, now there are a few things we need to do to get this data ready for analysis. Firstly, there are some new metrics that we can create from existing ones; uncontested marks, offensive pressure acts, etc. There are also some columns in this data set that won’t help us determine our roles including match information and Brownlow votes. I’ve also decided not to include height and weight in this analysis. This is a common way to determine player roles however I want this analysis not to be bias towards physical attributes and focus on what each player produces. If a short player is good at marking or a tall good at ground level then that’s completely fine.

At the moment our data is still in long format, we want to combine all our stats from each game to get players total stats for the season. We can then filter out players with not enough data to be reliable and finally we want to standardise our data. Standardising the data keeps it consistent and allows us to compare between different metrics by recording it in standard deviations above or below the league average in said stat.

# creating new columns, selecting desired columns, grouping the data, filtering and standardising
data_2022 <- raw_data_2022 %>%
  mutate(
    uncontested_marks = marks - contested_marks, 
    marks_outside_fifty = marks - marks_inside_fifty, 
    tackles_outside_fifty = tackles - tackles_inside_fifty, 
    contest_def_wins = contest_def_one_on_ones - contest_def_losses, 
    contest_off_losses = contest_off_one_on_ones - contest_off_wins, 
    off_half_pressure_acts = pressure_acts - def_half_pressure_acts, 
    games_played = sum(is.numeric(player_id))) %>% 
  select(-1:-18, -22:-24, -26, -43, -53, -74, -79:-81) %>% 
  group_by(
    player_id, 
    player_first_name, 
    player_last_name, 
    player_team) %>% 
  summarise(across(c(1:55), mean), across(c(56), sum)) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  filter(time_on_ground_percentage >= 50, games_played >= 10) %>%
  mutate(across(c(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60), function(x) (x/time_on_ground_percentage)*100)) %>% 
  mutate(across(c(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60), function(x) round((x-mean(c(x)))/sd(c(x)), digits = 5)))

After all this manipulation we can double check that our data set is clean and ready for analysis.

# final cleaning check
anyDuplicated(data_2022)
which(is.na(data_2022))

Broad roles

So time for the fun part, analysing our data. We have identified 51 stats for each player across the season and we want to see who is similar to who. We can do this using UMAP, a dimension reduction algorithm. This reduces our 51 variables into two dimensions, allowing us to visualise our data. Similar players will be closer in proximity.

# creating new data frame with relevant metrics for general mapping, umap
umap_data_2022 <- data_2022 %>% 
  select(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(data_2022, .)

So what does this show us? Well not every player is the exact same or they would all be in one cluster. And not all of them are different because we have some groupings. Now we can use a clustering algorithm, PAM in this case, to automatically identify and name these clusters in our data.

# pam the dataset, add it to the dataset, rename column and values
broad_position_2022 <- umap_data_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 5) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_data_2022) %>% 
  rename(broad_position = ".") %>% 
  mutate(broad_position = 
           ifelse(broad_position == 1, "Forwards", 
                  ifelse(broad_position == 2, "On-ballers", 
                         ifelse(broad_position == 3, "Rucks", 
                                ifelse(broad_position == 4, "Progressors", 
                                       ifelse(broad_position == 5, "Defenders", broad_position)))))) %>% 
  mutate(broad_position = factor(broad_position, levels = broad_position_custom_order))

Broad roles insights

So our players have been broken up into five broad clusters. Forwards, on ballers, progressors, rucks and defenders. While our traditional forwards, defenders and rucks stay the same, we now have on ballers and progressors.

The big men of the competition are a rare breed, coming in with the least number of players. Rucks top the charts in hitouts, ruck contests and hitouts to advantage. The reason they are so far away from our other data points is because these metrics are so specific to their role.

The defenders cluster really capture our last line of defence; players who are good at contested defensive one on ones, contested defensive wins, spoils and one percenters. They don’t often get the limelight but are the backbone of any good side.

On ballers are what comes to mind when you think of a midfielder. These guys are the stars of the comp, in and around the ball they excel at clearances, centre clearances, contested possessions and stoppage clearances.

Progressors have the largest number of players. From traditional positions this category includes wingers, half forwards and half backs. Guys that are going to get on the end of defenders or on ballers good work and transition the ball up the field. Progressors are guys each team looks to get the ball into the hands of and rank top of uncontested marks, rebounds, marks outside fifty, effective kicks and intercepts.

Finally the forwards, responsible for the most highlight worthy moments in our game, are the guys taking big marks, kicking bags and snapping goals from impossible angles. These guys are classified by shots at goal, goals, marks inside fifty and marks on lead.

Specific roles

So now let’s see if we can find even more specific roles within our broad positions. Let’s start by splitting our data set into each broad role and applying our dimension reduction algorithm again to each subset. This will compare players in each broad position between each other to identify any differences.

# split combined data set into broad roles
broad_position_2022_list <- broad_position_2022 %>% 
  rename(X3 = X1, X4 = X2) %>% 
  split(., .$broad_position)
# re selecting relevant columns
umap_forwards_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Forwards %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Forwards)
umap_on_ballers_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$`On-ballers` %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$`On-ballers`)
umap_progressors_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Progressors %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Progressors)
umap_defenders_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Defenders %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Defenders)
umap_rucks_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Rucks %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Rucks)

Let’s see how each of these looks.

Once again we certainly have a spread of data points in each of our broad positions. Lets apply our clustering algorithm to each of our broad roles and see what we can find.

# pam the broad roles
master_forwards_2022 <- umap_forwards_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_forwards_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Full-forward", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Connector", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Goal-sneak", specific_role))))
master_on_ballers_2022 <- umap_on_ballers_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_on_ballers_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Leader", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Enforcer", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Extractor", specific_role))))
master_progressors_2022 <- umap_progressors_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 4) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_progressors_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Quarter-back", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Orchestrator", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Impact",
                                ifelse(specific_role == 4, "Support", specific_role)))))
master_defenders_2022 <- umap_defenders_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_defenders_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Reliable", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Aggressive", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Full-back", specific_role))))
master_rucks_2022 <- umap_rucks_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 1) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_rucks_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Ruck-man", specific_role))

Specific role insights

Each of our broad positions have been broken down into a set of roles. Let’s check them out.

The one broad position we don’t find any trend in is our ruck men. Unfortunately there just isn’t enough ruckmen to find any groupings or trends. Teams will only play 1-2 ruckmen, each of whom plays a different role and is surrounded by a different team. Toby Nankervis of Richmond picks up disposals like a progressor, Darcy Cameron boots goals like a forward, Mark Blicavs plays like another on baller getting plenty of tackles and Tim English helps his defence out with intercepts and rebounds. Clustering ruckman would lead to inaccurate results… Each player is unique and applies their own skill set in their unique team setup.

Defenders have been broken down into three roles; aggressive, reliable and full back. Coming up with a creative name for full backs was just not needed. Think of Steven May, Darcy Moore, Jacob Weitering, Sam Taylor and Jeremy McGovern. Top for intercept marks, contested defensive wins and spoils they save more than a shopper on black friday. The key pillar for a functioning defence these are tasked with shutting down the opponents most important forward. We also see guys like Jeremy Howe, Tom Barrass and Jordan Ridley in this category. Often playing as the second tall defender in their team these high quality players are elite in aerial situations.

Ah the reliable defender, a team mate’s team mate, these guys rarely find themselves anywhere near a Brownlow vote but bet your bottom dollar the coach loves them. We are talking top of defensive one on one wins, spoils and one percenters. While they lack the aerial prowess of a full back these guys are the most consistent players in the comp. Think of Dylan Grimes, Jordan Butts, Harrison Petty or Tom McCartin. If you hear someone described as a ripper bloke they probably fall into this category.

Aggressive defenders… this is a nice way of describing the bloke who just did the thing that made you say “what the hell was that”. Pure chaos and entertainment these defenders do some of the craziest, dumbest and most impressive things on a footy field. If the ball goes near them make sure you are watching, they view the game like no other. Think of Sam Frost, Darcy Gardiner, Dane Rampe, Noah Balta or Tom Jonas. Their top metrics include defensive one on one losses, one percenters and spoils. Unfortunately catches also include reliable defenders or full backs who just didn’t have their best season.

Our on ballers are the most recognised position in the comp. AFLs most prestigious individual award goes to an on baller nearly every year. Our three on baller roles are leader, extractor and enforcer. Extractors resume list contested possessions, handballs and clearances. They win the ball for their team at ground level in highly contested areas distributing it out to other team mates. Think Joel Selwood, Travis Boak, Tom Liberatore and Jack Viney their tough as nails, win at all costs attitude often makes them captain material. We also see some big names like Sam Walsh, Touk Miller, Clayton Oliver and Patrick Cripps fall into this category. Guys that have the ability to be a leader, they may have to play this role for a weaker side, be in a team whose focus is on contested ball or are just so damn good at it.

Speaking of leaders, these blokes can do it all. Calling them a swiss army knife makes it sound they are all right at everything, these guys are elite at everything. Inside fifties, centre clearances, stoppage clearances, ground ball gets, contested possessions, tackles they can do it all. Andy Brayshaw, Marcus Bontempelli, Jack Steele, Christian Petracca, Callum Mills, you get the idea.

Finally we have enforcers, tackles and pressure acts are the aim of the game here. These players are tough inside bulls who bring the contest. They can also be given a tagging job where they shut down the opponents star mid. Think of Tom Atkins, Connor Nash, Hugh Greenwood and James Harmes.

Progressors have been split into four roles; support, impact, orchestrator and quarterback. Quarterbacks are exactly who you think of; Shannon Hurn, Sam Docherty, Jake Lloyd, Jake Sinclair, James Sicily and Tom Stewart. Top for effective kicks, rebounds and meters gained these guys are some of the best kicks in the game and are responsible for launching attacks from the back.

Orchestrators are our outside users, top for uncontested possessions, uncontested marks, and meters gained they are going to find space in the middle of the park and make the most of it. Think of Steele Sidebottom, Isaac Smith, Liam Bakar, Ed Langdon, Lachie Hunter and Josh Daicos. You will find these guys connecting transitional ball movement through the middle of the ground.

Impact players are one of the more interesting roles to come out of this analysis. Their top attributes include pressure acts, tackles outside the fifty, contested marks, score involvements, one percenters and clangers. These guys pop up when you least expect it at either end of the ground making a crucial tackle or slotting a clutch goal. Think of Jed Bews, Tom Powell, Bailey Williams, Mark O’Connor, Sam Durham. In reality a lot of players in this category are good players who haven’t quite developed to put out a full season at AFL level or aren’t quite being deployed in a role that suits them best.

Last but not least, supporters. Highly ranked in intercepts, rebounds, marks and defensive one on one wins these guys shut down attacks early for defenders and provide an option for other progressors to move the ball up the ground. Picture Jimmy Webster, Brayden Maynard, Jake Bowey, Blake Hardwick, Trent Rivers, John Noble, Zach Guthrie or Nathan Broad. Likely a younger player being primed to make the move to a reliable defender or quarterback role. Whether it’s sweeping up a loose attack or providing a marking option in transition these guys will be there when you need it.

Finally, we have forwards who are split up into full forwards, goal sneaks and connectors. Connectors are the front half quarterback if you will, the number 10. They stitch together the work of progressors with the other forwards. Think of Nick Holman, Dylan Moore, Gryan Miers, Charlie Spargo, Zac Bailey, Beau McCreery, or Sam Powell-Pepper. These guys excel at goal assists, forward 50 ground ball gets, tackles inside fifty, offensive half pressure acts and marks on a lead. They will find the ball on the ground or in the air near the fifty meter line and find a target inside fifty.

Goal sneaks are your typical small forwards, think of Izak Rankine, Kysiah Pickett, Sam Switkowski, Tyson Stengle or Tom Papley. They are the definition of pest but all class with the ball. Tackles inside fifty, forward fifty ground ball gets, offensive half pressure acts, shots at goal and goals they find a sneaky avenue to goal, pick the pocket of a defender or sweep up any scraps left by a full forward. Last but not least the full forward.

The jewel in a successful team’s crown full forwards are one of the most captivating roles on the field. Offensive one on ones, marks inside fifty, marks on a lead and goals, a full forward on his day is a site to behold. Ask for someone to name an AFL player and they will probably say a full forward. Lance Franklin, Josh Kennedy, Tom Hawkins, Taylor Walker, Charlie Dixon, Tom Lynch, Charlie Curnow or Aaron Naughton. Similar to our full back role, we also see midsize marking forwards in this role. Players like Jack Riewoldt, Jack Gunston, Toby Greene and Jamarra Ugle-Hagan. These guys profile very similar to a full forward, elite in the air and at kicking goals, but often play as the second tall in their team.

Concluding thoughts

So, is it possible to define player roles using data player roles rather than positions? Absolutely. Should we rename all the positions on the AFL field? …probably not. The player roles identified line up pretty accurately with existing player positions:

  • Full backs at full-back and centre half-back

  • Aggressive and reliable defenders in the back pocket

  • quarterbacks and supports across half back

  • Ruck men at ruck

  • Leader, enforcer and extractor at centre, rover and ruck-rover

  • Orchestrators on the wings

  • Connectors and impact players at half forward

  • Full forwards at full-forward and centre half-forward

  • Goal sneaks in the forward pocket

Can it be used to understand individual players and roles? Absolutely. What it has done for me is deepen my understanding of different roles and players and the skill-sets they possess. Similar analysis and classification could certainly be used on, say, the AFLs website, to describe different players. It could also present a way of measuring a player’s impact on a game not just by pure numbers, but by how well they are performing a role for their team.

This type of analysis could also be useful across AFL fantasy games which rely heavily on identifying and understanding player roles. We can certainly see trends across AFL Fantasy scoring and a player’s role. Leaders, extractors and quarterbacks often the most targeted roles come out on top as expected.

How could this analysis be improved or continued?

Those with access to even more comprehensive data could obviously conduct more accurate analysis and other mapping and clustering algorithms could also be tested. The mapping and clustering also produces slightly varied results on each iteration. A model could be trained to run the analysis and identify how often players land in each cluster to get a more accurate output . You could also try to answer; how each team’s most common lineup throughout the year broken down into roles? What about including previous years data as well? Do players’ roles evolve over their careers? With player roles changing throughout a season how could you measure periods of time where players have a different role?
